Import data

Character separated data

Comma separated data (.csv) is the most recommended data format, because it is

  1. widely supported,
  2. small,
  3. independent,
  4. stable, and
  5. sufficient for use in most cases.
read.csv()
read.table(sep = ",")
readr::read_csv()

Tab separated data is an alternative to .csv. Besides the advantages of .csv, tab separated data is friendly to humanâs eyes.

Download a demo dataset: https://pzhao.org/data/death_rate_tab.txt

read.delim()
read.table(sep = "\t")
readr::read_delim(delim = "\t")

Sometimes, your data might be separated by other characters.

Download a demo dataset: https://pzhao.org/data/death_rate_semicolon.txt

read.table(sep = ';')

Excel file

Can R directly read Excel files? If so, how?

Search online.

For reading Excel file (.xlsx, .xls), you can use the package âreadxlâ.

Download a demo dataset: https://pzhao.org/data/birdflu.xls

library("readxl")
bf <- read_excel("birdflu.xls")
bf_deaths <- read_excel("birdflu.xls", sheet = "death")

Another package, âxlsxâ is more powerful, which can not only read from, but also write to Excel file.

Before using âxlsxâ, java must be downloaded. Choose the right version1 from the download link.

library(xlsx)
bf <- read.xlsx("birdflu.xls", sheetName = 'case')
write.xlsx(cars, "birdflu.xls", sheetName = "my test", append = TRUE)

Overview data

The first step in analyzing data:

  1. Where are the data centred? How are they spread? Are they symmetric, skewed, bimodal?
  2. Are there outliers?
  3. Are the variables normally distributed?
  4. Are there any relationships between the variables? Are relationships between the variables linear? Which follow-up analysis should be applied?
  5. Do we need a transformation?
  6. Was the sampling effort approximately the same for each observation or variable?

Demo data: https://pzhao.org/data/diamonds2.zip

Meta data: originated from the data diamonds in the ggplot2 package.

diamonds2 <- read.csv("diamonds2.csv")

Clean data

Data type

diamonds2$x <- as.numeric(diamonds2$x)

unique(diamonds2$cut)
diamonds2$cut[diamonds2$cut == "Fare"] <- "Fair"
diamonds2$cut <- as.factor(diamonds2$cut)

unique(diamonds2$color)
diamonds2$color[diamonds2$color == "h"] <- "H"
diamonds2$color <- as.factor(diamonds2$color)

str(diamonds2)
summary(diamonds2)

Wrong spelling and case

Impossible values

diamonds2$carat[diamonds2$carat < 0] <- NA
diamonds2$x[diamonds2$x == 999] <- NA
summary(diamonds2)

Explore data

One dimensional data

Dotplot

A dotplot displays the original data.

dotchart(diamonds2$price)
beginr::plot_summary(diamonds2)

Histogram

A histogram shows the distribution of the data and gives an indication of normality.

hist(diamonds2$price)
beginr::plot_summary(diamonds2, base = "hist")

p_hist <- 
  diamonds %>% 
  ggplot() +
  geom_histogram(aes(price)) +
  xlim(0, 20000)

p_hist2 <- 
  diamonds %>% 
  ggplot() +
  geom_histogram(aes(price, after_stat(density))) +
  xlim(0, 20000)


p_density <- 
  p_hist2 + geom_density(aes(price), color = "blue")

Boxplot

A boxplot checks the center, the spread and outliers in a non-parametric way.

boxplot(diamonds2$price)
beginr::plot_summary(diamonds2, if_box = TRUE)

p_box <- 
  diamonds %>% 
  ggplot() +
  geom_boxplot(aes(price)) +
  xlim(0, 20000)

library(patchwork)
p_density / p_box + plot_layout(heights = c(10, 1))

Conditional:

diamonds$carat_class <- cut(diamonds$carat, 0:6)
p_box2 <- diamonds %>% 
  ggplot() +
  geom_boxplot(aes(price, fill = carat_class)) +
  xlim(0, 20000)
p_box / p_box2 + plot_layout(heights  = c(1, 5))

QQ plot

A Quantile-Quantile plot determines whether the data follow a particular distribution.

library(qqplotr)

diamonds2 %>% 
  ggplot() +
  geom_abline(aes(intercept = 0, slope = 1), color = "blue") +
  coord_fixed(ratio = 1, xlim = c(-3, 3), ylim = c(-3,3)) +
  stat_qq_point(aes(sample = scale(price)))

diamonds2 %>% 
  ggplot() +
  geom_abline(aes(intercept = 0, slope = 1), color = "blue") +
  coord_fixed(ratio = 1, xlim = c(-3, 3), ylim = c(-3,3)) +
  stat_qq_point(aes(sample = scale(depth)))

diamonds2[, -(2:4)] %>%
  gather() %>%
# diamonds2 %>% 
  ggplot() +
  geom_abline(aes(intercept = 0, slope = 1), color = "blue") +
  facet_wrap(~key, scales = "free") +
  stat_qq_point(aes(sample = value))

Two dimensional data

Scatterplot

A scatterplot explores a relationship between two variables.

diamonds2 %>% 
  ggplot() + 
  geom_point(aes(carat, price))

Pairplot

A pairplot explores relationships between every two variables.

pairs(diamonds2)
library(GGally)
diamonds2[, -(2:4)] %>% 
  ggpairs()

Coplot

A coplot explores the relationship between two variables for different values of a third variable.

coplot(price ~ carat|cut, data = diamonds2)
diamonds2 %>% 
  ggplot(aes(carat, price)) +
  geom_point() +
  facet_wrap(~cut)
set.seed(123)
v1 <- seq(0, 4, length = 100)
v3 <- rep(0:4, each = 20)
v2 <- - v1 + v3 + rnorm(100, 0, .25)
x <- data.frame(v1, v2, v3)
x %>% 
  ggplot(aes(v1, v2)) + 
  geom_point() +
  geom_smooth(method = "lm")

x %>% 
  ggplot(aes(v1, v2, color = as.factor(v3))) + 
  geom_point() +
  geom_smooth(method = "lm")

Outlier

An outlier is a data point with an extreme value compared to the rest of the dataset. It might incorrectly influence an analysis. It might be a hint for a great discovery.

An example for research of outliers: Peppa Pig

Step 1. Observation: Elephant Edmond and Emily. And Peppa Pig.

Step 2. Curiosity:

  • The names of Edmond and Emily begin with E, the initial of the spelling of elephant.
  • The names of Peppa begins with P, the initial of the spelling of pig.

Step 3. Hypothesis: The initial letter of any characterâ name in Peppa Pig is the same as the spelling of the animal.

Step 4. Collect and explore data:

Character Animal
Edmond elephant
Susie sheep
Candy cat
Danny dog
Pedro pony
Zoe zebra
Rebecca rabbit
Freddy fox
Delphine donkey
Wendy wolf

Step 5. Outlier: George Pig

  • Assumption: there must a word which begins with g and means pig.
  • Analysis: Look up the dictionary for the thesaurus for pig.

Step 6. Conclusion.

Transformation

Data transformation is often needed for finding the relationship between two variables.

Based on theory:

https://pzhao.org/data/speed.csv

speed <- read.csv("speed.csv")
speed %>% 
  ggplot(aes(t, y1)) +
  geom_point() + 
  geom_smooth(method = "lm")

speed %>% 
  ggplot(aes(t^2, y2)) +
  geom_point() + 
  geom_smooth(method = "lm")

Based on experience:

diamonds2 %>% 
  ggplot(aes(carat, price)) +
  geom_point() +
  scale_y_log10() +
  scale_x_log10() +
  facet_wrap(~cut) +
  geom_smooth(method = "lm")
